=========================================
INITIALIZER LIST vs UNIFORM INITIALIZATION
C++11 INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. Initializer List Initialization
----------------------------------

Syntax:
type variable = { values };

Example:
int a = {10};
vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};

✔ Uses assignment operator (=)
✔ Introduced in C++11 via std::initializer_list

-----------------------------------------

2. Uniform Initialization (Brace Initialization)
-------------------------------------------------

Syntax:
type variable { values };

Example:
int a {10};
vector<int> v {1, 2, 3, 4};

✔ No assignment operator
✔ Direct initialization using braces

-----------------------------------------

3. Key Difference
-----------------

Initializer List:
type var = { values };

Uniform Initialization:
type var { values };

-----------------------------------------

4. Common Behavior (IMPORTANT)
------------------------------

Both support:
✔ Prevent narrowing conversions

Example:
int x = {3.14};   // ❌ Error (narrowing)
int y {3.14};     // ❌ Error (narrowing)

-----------------------------------------

5. Why Uniform Initialization was introduced?
---------------------------------------------

✔ Consistent syntax for all types
✔ Avoids ambiguity (most vexing parse problem)
✔ Works for:
   - basic types
   - arrays
   - STL containers
   - classes

-----------------------------------------

6. Example with STL
-------------------

vector<int> v1 = {1,2,3};   // initializer list
vector<int> v2 {1,2,3};     // uniform initialization

-----------------------------------------

7. Example with Class
---------------------

class A {
public:
    int x;
    A(int v) : x(v) {}
};

A obj1 = {10};   // initializer list
A obj2 {10};     // uniform initialization

-----------------------------------------

8. Interview One-liner
-----------------------

Initializer list uses '=' with braces,
while uniform initialization uses direct braces {} without assignment,
both introduced in C++11 to provide consistent and safe initialization.

=========================================
QUICK REVISION
=========================================

1. = {} → initializer list
2. {} → uniform initialization
3. Both prevent narrowing conversion
4. Uniform is more consistent
